description.narrative:
Despite laws voted, multiple actions and means implemented, Burkinabè women participation in politics remains low and they are under-represented in terms of formal political leadership and electoral positions. However, women are at the center of politics, protests, associations and elections.
The objective of the study is to generate knowledge (both detailed and strategic) of contexts, structures and circumstances that condition the public participation of women and girls, as well as their involvement in formal decision-making and leadership roles in order to identify ways and means to strengthen female leadership in local arenas (villages, sectors, communes, provinces, regions). 
The study aims in particular to: 
- Explore the public participation of women and girls, including socio-cultural perceptions, psychological aspects, economic constraints, practices discriminatory practices, domestic violence, etc. ; 
- Document the perceptions of women regarding the inclusion and exclusion of leadership and civic participation positions; 
- Analyze the interactions between men and women, boys and girls, in contexts specific (school, meeting, workplace, work opportunities); 
- Develop case studies demonstrating women's leadership and the practices of decentralization (women and political parties, girls as youth leaders, double the household burden, community life, etc.); 
- Analyze the constraints and opportunities of the Common Gender Fund (FCG) with regard to effective application of support for the empowerment of women and youth; 
- Analyze the involvement of women and young people in security challenges in arenas local; 
- Document best practices to strengthen leadership and empowerment women and youth policy by focusing on local initiatives and practices; and 
- Make concrete recommendations regarding activities, actions and specific organizations, to strengthen female leadership in Burkina Faso, particularly in relation to the Gender Common Fund.
